The Core Problem: GraalPy is Not CPython
Layer 1: The ctypes Callback Problem (Current Blocker)

pypdfium2 wraps libpdfium, a native C library. To pass Python data (such as a BytesIO buffer) into that C library, it relies on ctypes callbacks — Python functions converted into C function pointers at runtime.

Simplified Example
# Inside pypdfium2 (simplified)
GetBlock = ctypes.CFUNCTYPE(...)      # Define C function signature
callback = GetBlock(my_python_function)  # Convert Python function → C pointer
Failure Point

This conversion is not supported in GraalPy.

CPython provides a stable C ABI that allows Python functions to be exposed as callable C function pointers.
GraalPy runs on the JVM and does not expose a compatible C ABI.
As a result, native code cannot call back into Python via function pointers.
Observed Error
Cannot convert Object pointer to native
Key Insight

Your fix:

POINTER(None) → c_void_p

only resolves a type annotation issue, not the core problem.

The failure is architectural, not syntactic.
It cannot be patched with small fixes.

Layer 2: PDF Loading Path Has No Escape

You identified a potential workaround:

Use a file path instead of an in-memory buffer
This would ideally trigger:
FPDF_LoadDocument (path-based)
instead of FPDF_LoadMemDocument (buffer + callback)
Why This Matters
Function	Requires Callbacks
FPDF_LoadMemDocument	Yes
FPDF_LoadDocument	No
The Problem

pypdfium2.PdfDocument abstracts this decision:

It inspects input types internally
It may still convert file paths into buffers
It likely routes everything through the memory-loading path
Implication

Even if docling passes a file path:

You cannot guarantee callback-free execution
The callback requirement may still be triggered internally
