Layer 4: The Architectural Mismatch
GraalVM Strengths
Polyglot execution (Java ↔ Python ↔ JS)
JVM-based interoperability
Works well with:
Pure Python
Simple C extensions
Docling Stack Reality

Docling depends on:

pypdfium2 (native + callbacks)
torch (heavy native backend)
lxml (C extensions)
Other low-level libraries
Core Conflict
GraalPy	Docling Stack
JVM-based runtime	CPython-native ecosystem
Limited C ABI support	Heavy reliance on native bindings
No callback-compatible ctypes	Requires callbacks
Conclusion

These systems are fundamentally incompatible.

GraalPy is suitable for:

Pure Python logic
Lightweight extensions

Docling is built on:

Deep native integrations
CPython-specific behavior
Bottom Line
This is not a bug
This is not patchable
This is an architectural incompatibility
If you want GraalVM to work:

You must either:

Replace native-heavy dependencies (PDFium, Torch, etc.)
Or introduce a native bridge layer outside GraalPy
Recommendation

Start with:

A minimal proof-of-concept (custom C extractor), or
A migration to MuPDF

before attempting full pipeline compatibility.
